# Question2: How much sugar intake should a student maintain to get an optimal score?

# Categorize sugar intake
data$sugar_category <- cut(
  data$sugar,
  breaks = quantile(data$sugar, probs = seq(0, 1, 0.333), na.rm = TRUE),
  labels = c("Low", "Medium", "High"),
  include.lowest = TRUE
)
# E.g if sugar intake is 0.5, it falls in the medium category
# E.g if sugar intake is 0.8, it falls in the high category
# E.g if sugar intake is 0.2, it falls in the low category
# Boxplot of scores by sugar category using ggplot
# Add points to show actual data
ggplot(data, aes(x = sugar_category, y = score, fill = sugar_category)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, height = 0, alpha = 0.5, colour="red" ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Scores by Sugar Intake Category",
       x = "Sugar Intake Category",
       y = "Score") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Low" = "lightblue", "Medium" = "lightgreen", "High" = "darkcyan"))

# Define the scope of predictors
scope <- ~ age + gender + bacII + sugar + coffee + n_coffee + cour + tp + td + self_study
# Fit the null model (intercept-only)
null_model <- lm(score ~ 1, data = data)
# Perform stepwise selection
stepwise_model <- step(null_model, scope = scope, direction = "both", trace = 1)

h<-influence(md5)$h
sum(h)
## [1] 10
# what is h? :answer: h is the leverage of the model. It is a measure of how far away the independent variable values of an observation are from those of the other observations.
# It is used to detect influential points in the model.sum(h) = 10 means that there are 10 influential points in the model. the higher the influence point means the more the model is affected by that point.

#plot leverage
plot(h, xlab="i", ylab="leverage", cex.axis=1.5, cex.lab=1.5)
abline(h=sum(h)/nrow(data), lty=2)

## Look at BacIIE variable, it has an extreme odds ratio. This is not right for the interpretation of the model which means all every student who obtained grade E in BacII has incredibly high odds of scoring 75 or above. This is not realistic.


library(glmnet)
## Warning: package 'glmnet' was built under R version 4.3.3
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loaded glmnet 4.1-8
# Prepare the data
X <- model.matrix(~ coffee + n_coffee + sugar + gender + bacII + tp + cour + td - 1, data = data)
y <- data$score_binary

# Standardize predictors (glmnet does this by default, but it's good to confirm)
X <- scale(X)

# Fit Lasso model using glmnet
lasso_model <- glmnet(X, y, family = "binomial", alpha = 1)

# Perform cross-validation to find optimal lambda
cv_lasso <- cv.glmnet(X, y, family = "binomial", alpha = 1)

# Extract the best lambda (optimal regularization strength)
best_lambda <- cv_lasso$lambda.min
print(paste("Best lambda:", best_lambda))
## [1] "Best lambda: 0.00779459338701582"
# Extract coefficients for the best lambda
lasso_coef <- coef(lasso_model, s = best_lambda)
print(lasso_coef)
